Here are the authoritative public test cases for feature3_transaction_logging:
{
  "description": "Running units of work as transactions through the logging decorator. Beginning a transaction emits a begin entry. A transaction that completes normally emits a commit entry after its body; a transaction whose body requests a rollback emits a rollback entry instead. Statements issued inside a transaction body are logged in place, between the begin entry and the eventual commit/rollback entry, using the same operation/SQL and bound-value logging as outside a transaction. Multiple transactions run in sequence produce their entries in execution order. All emitted log lines are written to standard output.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "commands": [
          {
            "op": "transaction",
            "rollback": false,
            "body": []
          },
          {
            "op": "transaction",
            "rollback": true,
            "body": []
          },
          {
            "op": "transaction",
            "rollback": false,
            "body": [
              {
                "op": "execute",
                "identifier": 2,
                "sql": "INSERT INTO test VALUES (?, ?);",
                "parameters": 2,
                "binders": [
                  {
                    "bind": "long",
                    "index": 1,
                    "value": 1
                  },
                  {
                    "bind": "string",
                    "index": 2,
                    "value": "Alec"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "TRANSACTION BEGIN\nTRANSACTION COMMIT\nTRANSACTION BEGIN\nTRANSACTION ROLLBACK\nTRANSACTION BEGIN\nEXECUTE\n INSERT INTO test VALUES (?, ?);\n [1, Alec]\nTRANSACTION COMMIT\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the authoritative public test cases for feature2_query_logging:
{
  "description": "Issuing a read/query statement through the logging decorator. The forwarded query emits a single log entry naming the query operation followed by the SQL text. When no bound parameter values are supplied, no value entry is emitted. The log line is written to standard output.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "commands": [
          {
            "op": "query",
            "identifier": 3,
            "sql": "SELECT * FROM test",
            "parameters": 0
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "QUERY\n SELECT * FROM test\n"
    }
  ]
}

Here are the authoritative public test cases for feature1_execute_logging:
{
  "description": "Wrapping a base data-access driver in a logging decorator and issuing one or more write statements. Each forwarded write emits a log entry naming the write operation followed by the SQL text; when bound parameter values are supplied for that statement, an additional log entry lists those bound values in binding order. A write whose parameter-binding step binds nothing emits only the operation/SQL entry and no value entry. Every emitted log line is written to standard output in the order produced.",
  "cases": [
    {
      "input": {
        "commands": [
          {
            "op": "execute",
            "identifier": 2,
            "sql": "INSERT INTO test VALUES (?, ?);",
            "parameters": 2,
            "binders": [
              {
                "bind": "long",
                "index": 1,
                "value": 1
              },
              {
                "bind": "string",
                "index": 2,
                "value": "Alec"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "op": "execute",
            "identifier": 2,
            "sql": "INSERT INTO test VALUES (?, ?);",
            "parameters": 2,
            "binders": []
          }
        ]
      },
      "expected_output": "EXECUTE\n INSERT INTO test VALUES (?, ?);\n [1, Alec]\nEXECUTE\n INSERT INTO test VALUES (?, ?);\n"
    }
  ]
}

